```

For non-product_bug categories, do NOT include `bug_details`.

**If category is `test_bug`**, you MUST include a `suggested_fix` object to help engineers fix the test.
Use the traceback to identify the file and function. If the OCS-CI source code is accessible
(see "OCS-CI Source Code Access" section above), you MUST read the actual source file from the
release branch using `git show` before writing the fix. This is critical for accuracy — do NOT
guess line numbers or code structure from memory. Read the file, find the exact function, and
produce a correct unified diff. Also check `master` — if already fixed there, note that a
cherry-pick is needed.

```
"suggested_fix": {
    "file": "<path to the file from the traceback, e.g. ocs_ci/ocs/bucket_utils.py>",
    "function": "<function name where the fix goes, e.g. craft_s3_command>",
    "line": <exact line number where the change starts — MUST be verified by reading the file>,
    "description": "<clear explanation of what's wrong and how to fix it>",
    "code_snippet": "<ONLY the new or changed code — NOT the entire file. Show just the lines to add or modify, ready to paste>",
    "diff": "<unified diff showing the fix with context lines, using - for removed and + for added lines>",
    "fixed_on_master": <true/false — whether master branch already has the fix>,
    "needs_cherry_pick": <true/false — true if fixed on master but not on the release branch>
}
```

**IMPORTANT — accurate line numbers**: Do NOT use the line number from the traceback blindly.
The traceback line is where the *error was raised*, not necessarily where the *fix* should go.
After reading the file with `git show`, count the actual line number of the code you are changing.
Use `git show <branch>:<file> | head -N` or `grep -n` to verify the exact line.

For non-test_bug categories, do NOT include `suggested_fix`.

Do NOT end with narrative text. The LAST thing in your response MUST be the closing ``` of the JSON block.
